`crates/ctx-scan/tests/` is the integration-test suite for ctx-scan's whole pipeline — walking, hashing, summarizing, reconciling orphans, and the stop-hook — verified end-to-end rather than unit by unit. Depending on this directory buys confidence that the public entry points (`walk_dir`, `summarize`, `check_run`, `update_run`, `prune_run`, `stop_hook`) behave correctly together across fresh, stale, edited, and deleted-source scenarios.

All test files share `common/`'s `FakeFs` and `StubAgent`/recording agent as their hermetic substitutes for disk and LLM calls; any test claiming "no model call" or "no disk I/O" is trusting that these fakes stay faithful to the real `Fs`/`Agent` traits. Several files independently re-derive the same lifecycle facts and rely on them holding across the whole pipeline: `.ctxignore` is seeded once from `.gitignore` then decouples (walker.rs), hashes and summaries can drift apart so hash-freshness alone doesn't guarantee summaries exist (scan.rs), and pruning/reconciliation never invokes the model (reconcile.rs, scan.rs, stop_hook.rs all assert some form of this). `intent.md` and `.cache/`/`.reports/` are exempted from orphan-pruning across both scan.rs and reconcile.rs — a change to that exemption list must be reflected in both.

A typical cross-cutting change — e.g. altering what counts as "stale" or what triggers regeneration — touches scan.rs (core semantics), stop_hook.rs (reporting-only consumer), and possibly reconcile.rs (pruning consumer), since all three build on the same `check_run`/`update_run` contract from different angles.

No intent.md exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.